## credsentinel — auditd watch rules for the deployed honeytoken decoys.
##
## credsentinel SHIPS these rules but NEVER loads them into the kernel. Install
## them yourself after review (see deploy/README.md). Loading audit rules modifies
## kernel audit state and is a privileged operation.
##
## WHY a second tripwire: credsentinel's primary trip signal is the decoy's atime
## advancing (something read it). An attacker who mounts the filesystem `noatime`,
## or copies the decoy with an atime-preserving tool, can defeat the atime check.
## An auditd read watch (-p r) records the read at the syscall level, independent
## of atime, and names the reading process. A read of any decoy below is a
## near-zero-false-positive breach indicator → assume compromise, rotate from a
## clean device, escalate to bpfsentry's offline check.
##
## PATHS: these are the DEFAULT decoy locations (HoneytokenDir = the home dir).
## Replace `/home/CHANGEME` with the real user's home, OR generate this file for
## the exact deployed paths straight from the manifest:
##
##     credsentinel deploy ...            # writes the manifest
##     # then emit per-decoy auditctl lines from the recorded paths:
##     #   honeytoken.AuditdRules(manifest)   (the same lines, exact paths)
##
## auditd resolves -w paths at load time, so each must exist (deploy first).

-w /home/CHANGEME/.aws/credentials.bak -p rwa -k credsentinel_honeytoken
-w /home/CHANGEME/.kube/decoy.kubeconfig -p rwa -k credsentinel_honeytoken
-w /home/CHANGEME/.config/app/.env.decoy -p rwa -k credsentinel_honeytoken
